title: Update Device.cs
message:
Update Device.cs

The handler function can be called for two reasons: 1) service discovery succeeded or 2) service discovery failed. In the later case `args.Error` will not be null and `_nativeDevice.Services` may be null. In that case, we cannot return from the handler without setting the result on the TaskCompletionSource. Doing so will certainly cause a deadlock because this task will never complete. The fact that the event handler is removed by `_nativeDevice.DiscoveredService -= handler;` ensures that. 

If an error occurs, the code will not complete with an empty list of services. Then the caller can do what they choose with that.

title: Use the Client Characteristic Configuration
message:
Use the Client Characteristic Configuration

The [BLE GATT Descriptors spec](https://developer.bluetooth.org/gatt/descriptors/Pages/DescriptorsHomePage.aspx) defines a specific Descriptor that clients should use to write [Client Characteristic Configurations](https://developer.bluetooth.org/gatt/descriptors/Pages/DescriptorViewer.aspx?u=org.bluetooth.descriptor.gatt.client_characteristic_configuration.xml) such as enabling notifications or indications. Although it is sometimes (often) the first descriptor that appears in `_nativeCharacteristic.Descriptors`, order isn't guaranteed. For some devices (including the one I'm working with now), another descriptor comes first and grabbing the first one out of the list will result in never actually enabling notifications on the characteristic.

title: This is mainly to handle various GATT errors on the Android side. In the case of…
message:
This is mainly to handle various GATT errors on the Android side. In the case of GATT error (I usually see the generic error 133), the action should be to raise an error event to possible async extension calls (both ConnectAsync and DisconnectAsync now listen for the error event). If we don't do this and exit, the code would fall through to the switch statement, which would erroneously fall into the "disconnect" clause (since the enum for the unset [in the case of error] state 0 is the enum for disconnected). I close the gatt in this case, which seems to lead to fewer zombie gatts (previously, various errors would cause zombie gatts to hand around, holding on to a connection that you couldn't access, even sometimes past the lifetime of the app, requiring a phone reboot if max connections [6 on some phone models] was reached.)

iOS just raises the error event in the case of a corresponding failure to connect event from central.
